# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chrysler-valiant
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chrysler-valiant/1963-armstrong-500] The **1963 Armstrong 500** was the fourth running of the Armstrong 500 touring car race.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1963-armstrong-500] After the 1962 race, the Phillip Island Grand Prix Circuit was too damaged to continue to stage the race, forcing it to move to a new location, the Mount Panorama Circuit just outside Bathurst with a new organising club, the Australian Racing Drivers Club.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1963-armstrong-500] The race was open to standard production sedans with four classes based on the purchase price (in Australian pounds) of the vehicle.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1963-armstrong-500] Bob Jane and Harry Firth were the first team to complete the full race distance, taking victory in Class C in their factory backed Ford Cortina GT, the change of both vehicle and circuit making no difference to their result of the previous year.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1963-armstrong-500] While outright victories were not to be recognised until years later, they had completed a hat-trick of 'first to the line' wins.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1963-armstrong-500] The bigger cars moved down the alphabet, the smaller cars moved into classes A and B.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1963-armstrong-500] Ford Falcons disappeared from the race, replaced by an influx of smaller, more versatile Ford Cortinas.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1963-armstrong-500] As in 1962 the Fords were the biggest threat, shaping up to be faster than the larger D Class cars which included Chrysler Valiants and Studebaker Larks.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1963-armstrong-500] Class A was for cars that cost less £900.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1963-armstrong-500] It comprised Fiat 770, Morris 850, Triumph Herald and Volkswagen Beetle.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1963-armstrong-500] The £901 to £1,000 class featured 1.5 litre Ford Cortina, Morris Cooper and Morris Major Elite, Renault R8 and Simca Aronde.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1963-armstrong-500] The £1,001 to £1,200 class was contested by Ford Cortina GT, Holden EH S4 and Holden FB.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1963-armstrong-500] The £1,201 to £2,000 class featured Chrysler Valiant, Ford Zephyr, Humber Super Snipe, Peugeot 404, Studebaker Lark, Vauxhall Velox and Vauxhall VX 4/90.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1963-armstrong-500] The race became the first Ford vs Holden head-to-head fight, with the works Cortina of defending race champions Bob Jane and Harry Firth winning by a lap over the first EH Holden of Ralph Sach and Fred Morgan with a second Cortina on the same lap.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1963-armstrong-500] It was a third consecutive victory for Jane and Firth, each victory coming in a different model and back-to-back for the factory Ford team.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1963-armstrong-500] Second place was the closest Holden would get to a win until the breakthrough in 1968.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1963-armstrong-500] Chrysler got its first class win with the Valiant of Tony Reynolds and Tony Allen with Geoff Russell driving the factory prepared Ford Zephyr again narrowly missing out on the Class D win.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1963-armstrong-500] The new Morris Coopers saw the Mini break out of the entry level class and gave Doug Chivas his first class win, co-driving with Ken Wilkinson in Class B, defeating the 1.5 litre Cortinas, ominously just a lap behind the Valiant and the Zephyr.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1963-armstrong-500] In the small class, Volkswagen again defeated the Morris 850s with Barry Ferguson and Bill Ford taking first place ahead of the Mini of Don Holland and Lindsay Little.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1966-gallaher-500] The **1966 Gallaher 500** was an endurance motor race for production cars, held on 2 October 1966 at the Mount Panorama Circuit just outside Bathurst, New South Wales in Australia.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1966-gallaher-500] It was the seventh running of the Bathurst 500 race and the first time that the event had been staged under the Gallaher 500 name.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1966-gallaher-500] 250 examples of a particular model had to be registered for a vehicle to be eligible for the race, up from the 100 examples required in previous years.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1966-gallaher-500] The race was dominated by the Morris Cooper S.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1966-gallaher-500] It was won by the BMC entered example of Finnish rally star Rauno Aaltonen and experienced Australian Mini racer Bob Holden a lap ahead of Fred Gibson and Bill Stanley, leading home a flotilla of Cooper Ss that filled the first nine outright race positions.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1966-gallaher-500] The best non-Mini was a Chrysler Valiant, some six laps behind Aaltonen and Holden in tenth position.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1966-gallaher-500] It was while spectating this race from Forrest's Elbow that an on leave from the army Peter Brock decided that he wanted to be a motor racing driver when his National Service was finished.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1966-gallaher-500] Brock would go on to make his Bathurst 500 debut in 1969 and would go on to win the race a record 9 times.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1966-gallaher-500] Cars competed in four classes based on the purchase price of the vehicle in Australian dollars.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1966-gallaher-500] The Up to $1,800 class was contested by Datsun Bluebird 1300, Fiat 850, 1.2 litre Ford Cortina, Morris Mini De Luxe and Morris 850.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1966-gallaher-500] The $1,801 to $2,040 class featured 1.5 litre Ford Cortina, Hillman Minx, Isuzu Bellett, Morris Cooper, Prince Skyline, Renault R8 and Toyota Corona.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1966-gallaher-500] The $2,041 to $2,700 class entry list was dominated by the Morris Cooper S, but also included a Fiat 1500, and a Toyota Crown.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1966-gallaher-500] The $2,701 to $4,000 class featured Chrysler Valiant, Holden HD X2, Studebaker Lark, Triumph 2000 and Volvo 122S.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1970-hardie-ferodo-500] The **1970 Hardie-Ferodo 500** was the 11th running of the Bathurst 500 touring car race.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1970-hardie-ferodo-500] It was held on 4 October 1970 at the Mount Panorama Circuit just outside Bathurst.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1970-hardie-ferodo-500] The race was open to standard production sedans competing in five classes based on the purchase price of the vehicle (in Australian dollars).
[src:chrysler-valiant/1970-hardie-ferodo-500] Allan Moffat won his first Bathurst endurance race, leading home Bruce McPhee in a one-two result for the Ford works team and their Ford XW Falcon GTHO Phase II's.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1970-hardie-ferodo-500] It was the fifth Phillip Island / Bathurst 500 victory for the factory team.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1970-hardie-ferodo-500] Third, a lap behind the Fords, was Don Holland driving a Holden LC Torana GTR XU-1.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1970-hardie-ferodo-500] Defending winners Colin Bond and Tony Roberts drove separate cars in the event.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1970-hardie-ferodo-500] Bond finished 16th in his Holden Dealer Team Torana GTR XU-1 after having led the early laps, while Roberts was lucky to survive a spectacular accident when his Ford Falcon GTHO crashed at Skyline only 6 laps from the finish.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1970-hardie-ferodo-500] The Falcon spun backwards, leapt over the guard rail and rolled about 50 metres down the mountain before being stopped by a tree.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1970-hardie-ferodo-500] It was made up of Datsun 1200s, 1.3 litre Ford Escorts, Mazda 1300s and Toyota Corollas.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1970-hardie-ferodo-500] A Datsun 1200 won the class with an average lap time of 3 minutes, 26 seconds.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1970-hardie-ferodo-500] The $1,961 to $2,400 class consisted of Datsun 1600, Fiat 128, Ford Cortina and 2.6 litre Holden Torana.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1970-hardie-ferodo-500] The $2,401 to $3,150 class saw a mix of two barrel carburettor Chrysler Valiant Pacer, 1.6 litre Ford Escort, 3.1 litre Holden Torana and Morris Cooper S.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1970-hardie-ferodo-500] The $3,151 to $4,100 class featured only the four barrel carburettor Chrysler Valiant Pacer, a Fiat 125 and a Triumph 2.5 PI although a Ford Capri was also entered but did not start.
[src:chrysler-valiant/1970-hardie-ferodo-500] Apart from a single BMW 2800 and a Holden Monaro the class consisted only of Ford Falcon GTHO Phase II.
[src:chrysler-valiant/acrylic-enamel] Typically the term "enamel paint" is used to describe oil-based covering products, usually with a significant amount of gloss in them, however recently many latex or water-based paints have adopted the term as well.
[src:chrysler-valiant/acrylic-enamel] The term today means "hard surfaced paint" and usually is in reference to paint brands of higher quality, floor coatings of a high gloss finish, or spray paints.
[src:chrysler-valiant/acrylic-enamel] Most enamel paints are alkyd resin based.
[src:chrysler-valiant/acrylic-enamel] Some enamel paints have been made by adding varnish to oil-based paint.
[src:chrysler-valiant/acrylic-enamel] Although "enamels" and "painted enamel" in art normally refer to vitreous enamel, in the 20th century some artists used commercial enamel paints in art, including Pablo Picasso (mixing it with oil paint), Hermann-Paul, Jackson Pollock, and Sidney Nolan.
[src:chrysler-valiant/acrylic-enamel] *The Trial* (1947) is one of a number of works by Nolan to use enamel paint, usually Ripolin, a commercial paint not intended for art, also Picasso's usual brand.
[src:chrysler-valiant/acrylic-enamel] Some "enamel paints" are now produced specifically for artists.
[src:chrysler-valiant/acrylic-enamel] Enamels paints can also refer to nitrocellulose based paints, one of the first modern commercial paints of the 20th century.
[src:chrysler-valiant/acrylic-enamel] They have since been superseded by new synthetic coatings like alkyd, acrylic and vinyl, due to toxicity, safety, and conservation (tendency to age yellow) concerns.
[src:chrysler-valiant/acrylic-enamel] In art has been used also by Pollock with the commercial paint named Duco.
[src:chrysler-valiant/acrylic-enamel] The artist experimented and created with many types of commercial or house paints during his career.
[src:chrysler-valiant/acrylic-enamel] Nitro-cellulose enamels are also commonly known as modern lacquers.
[src:chrysler-valiant/acrylic-enamel] Enamel paint comes in a variety of hues and can be custom blended to produce a particular tint.
[src:chrysler-valiant/acrylic-enamel] It is also available in water-based and solvent-based formulations, with solvent-based enamel being more prevalent in industrial applications.
[src:chrysler-valiant/acrylic-enamel] For the greatest results, use a high-quality brush, roller, or spray gun when applying enamel paint.
[src:chrysler-valiant/acrylic-enamel] When dried, enamel paint forms a durable, hard-wearing surface that resists chipping, fading, and discoloration, making it a great choice for a wide range of surfaces and applications.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] An **alternator** (or **synchronous generator**) is an electrical generator that converts mechanical energy to electrical energy in the form of alternating current (AC).
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] For reasons of cost and simplicity, most alternators use a rotating magnetic field with a stationary armature.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The rotor coil is externally excited by a small direct current (DC), while the AC is generated in the stationary coils.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Occasionally, a linear alternator or a rotating armature with a stationary magnetic field is used.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Although any AC electrical generator might be called an alternator, usually the term refers to small rotating machines driven by automotive and other internal combustion engines.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The term usually applies those types with externally excited rotor coils.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] An alternator that uses a permanent magnet for its magnetic field is called a magneto.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Alternators in power stations driven by steam turbines are called turbo-alternators.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Large 50 or 60 Hz three-phase alternators in power plants generate most of the world's electric power, which is distributed by electric power grids.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Alternating current generating systems were known in simple forms from the discovery of the magnetic induction of electric current in the 1830s.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Rotating generators naturally produced alternating current, but since there was little use for it, it was normally converted into direct current via the addition of a commutator in the generator.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The early machines were developed by pioneers such as Michael Faraday and Hippolyte Pixii.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Faraday developed the "rotating rectangle", whose operation was *heteropolar* – each active conductor passed successively through regions where the magnetic field was in opposite directions.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Lord Kelvin and Sebastian Ferranti also developed early alternators, producing frequencies between 100 and 300 Hz.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The late 1870s saw the introduction of the first large-scale electrical systems with central generation stations to power Arc lamps, used to light whole streets, factory yards, or the interior of large warehouses.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Some, such as Yablochkov arc lamps introduced in 1878, ran better on alternating current, and the development of these early AC generating systems was accompanied by the first use of the word "alternator".
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Supplying the proper amount of voltage from generating stations in these early systems was left up to the engineer's skill in "riding the load".
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] In 1883 the Ganz Works invented the constant voltage generator that could produce a stated output voltage, regardless of the value of the actual load.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The introduction of transformers in the mid-1880s led to the widespread use of alternating current and the use of alternators needed to produce it.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] After 1891, polyphase alternators were introduced to supply currents of multiple differing phases.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Later alternators were designed for various alternating current frequencies between sixteen and about one hundred hertz for use with arc lighting, incandescent lighting, and electric motors.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Specialized radio frequency alternators like the Alexanderson alternator were developed as longwave radio transmitters around World War 1 and used in a few high power wireless telegraphy stations before vacuum tube transmitters replaced them.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] A conductor moving relative to a magnetic field develops an electromotive force (EMF) in it (Faraday's Law).
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] This EMF reverses its polarity when it moves under magnetic poles of opposite polarity.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Typically, a rotating magnet, called the rotor, turns within a stationary set of conductors, called the stator, wound in coils on an iron core.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The field cuts across the conductors, generating an induced EMF (electromotive force), as the mechanical input causes the rotor to turn.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The rotating magnetic field induces an AC voltage in the stator windings.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Since the currents in the stator windings vary in step with the position of the rotor, an alternator is a synchronous generator.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The rotor's magnetic field may be produced by permanent magnets or by a field coil electromagnet.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Automotive alternators use a rotor winding, which allows control of the alternator's generated voltage by varying the current in the rotor field winding.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Permanent magnet machines avoid the loss due to magnetizing current in the rotor, but are restricted in size due to the cost of the magnet material.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Since the permanent magnet field is constant, the terminal voltage varies directly with the speed of the generator.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Brushless AC generators are usually larger than those used in automotive applications.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] An automatic voltage control device controls the field current to keep the output voltage constant.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] If the output voltage from the stationary armature coils drops due to an increase in demand, more current is fed into the rotating field coils through the voltage regulator (VR).
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] This increases the magnetic field around the field coils, which induces a greater voltage in the armature coils.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Thus, the output voltage is brought back up to its original value.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Alternators used in central power stations also control the field current to regulate reactive power and to help stabilize the power system against the effects of momentary faults.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Often, there are three sets of stator windings, physically offset so that the rotating magnetic field produces a three-phase current, displaced by one-third of a period with respect to each other.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] One cycle of alternating current is produced each time a pair of field poles passes over a point on the stationary winding.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The relation between speed and frequency is $N=120f/P$ , where f is the frequency in Hz (cycles per second).
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] P is the number of poles (2, 4, 6, ...), and N is the rotational speed in revolutions per minute (r/min).
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Old descriptions of alternating current systems sometimes give the frequency in terms of alternations per minute, counting each half-cycle as one *alternation*; so 12,000 alternations per minute corresponds to 100 Hz.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] An alternator's output frequency depends on the number of poles and the rotational speed.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The speed corresponding to a particular frequency is called the *synchronous speed*.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Alternators may be classified by the method of excitation, number of phases, the type of rotation, cooling method, and their application.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] There are two main ways to produce the magnetic field used in the alternators: by using permanent magnets, which create their persistent magnetic field, or by using field coils.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The alternators that use permanent magnets are specifically called magnetos.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] In other alternators, wound field coils form an electromagnet to produce the rotating magnetic field.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] A device that uses permanent magnets to produce alternating current is called a permanent magnet alternator (PMA).
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] A permanent magnet generator (PMG) may produce either alternating current or direct current if it has a commutator.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] This method of excitation consists of a smaller direct-current (DC) generator fixed on the same shaft as the alternator.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The DC generator generates a small amount of electricity, just enough to *excite* the field coils of the connected alternator to generate electricity.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] A variation of this system is a type of alternator that uses direct current from a battery for initial excitation upon start-up, after which the alternator becomes self-excited.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] This method of excitation consists of a smaller alternating-current (AC) generator fixed on the same shaft as the alternator.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The AC stator generates a small amount of field coil excitation current, which is induced in the rotor and rectified to DC by a bridge rectifier built in to the windings where it excites the field coils of the larger connected alternator to generate electricity.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] This system has the advantage of not requiring brushes, which increases service life, although with a slightly lower overall efficiency.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] This method depends on residual magnetism retained in the iron core to generate a weak magnetic field, which would allow a weak voltage to be generated.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] This voltage is used to excite the field coils so the alternator can generate stronger voltage as part of its *build up* process.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] After the initial AC voltage buildup, the field is supplied with rectified voltage from the alternator.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] A brushless alternator is composed of two alternators built end-to-end on one shaft.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Until 1966, alternators used brushes with rotating field.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] With the advancement in semiconductor technology, brushless alternators are possible.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Smaller brushless alternators may look like one unit, but the two parts are readily identifiable in the large versions.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The main alternator is the larger of the two sections, and the smaller one is the exciter.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The exciter has stationary field coils and a rotating armature (power coils).
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The main alternator uses the opposite configuration with a rotating field and stationary armature.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] A bridge rectifier, called the rotating rectifier assembly, is mounted on the rotor.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Neither brushes nor slip rings are used, which reduces the number of wearing parts.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The main alternator has a rotating field and a stationary armature (power generation windings).
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Varying the amount of current through the stationary exciter field coils varies the 3-phase output from the exciter.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] This output is rectified by a rotating rectifier assembly mounted on the rotor, and the resultant DC supplies the rotating field of the main alternator and hence alternator output.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The result is that a small DC exciter current indirectly controls the output of the main alternator.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Another way to classify alternators is by the number of phases of their output voltage.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The output can be single-phase or polyphase.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Three-phase alternators are the most common, but polyphase alternators can be two-phase, six-phase, or more.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The revolving part of alternators can be the armature or the magnetic field.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The revolving armature type has the armature wound on the rotor, where the winding moves through a stationary magnetic field.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The revolving armature type is not often used.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The revolving field type has a magnetic field on the rotor to rotate through a stationary armature winding.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The stationary armature can be wound for any convenient medium voltage level, up to tens of thousands of volts; manufacture of slip ring connections for more than a few thousand volts is costly and inconvenient.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Many alternators are cooled by ambient air, forced through the enclosure by an attached fan on the shaft that drives the alternator.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] In vehicles such as transit buses, a heavy demand on the electrical system may require a large alternator to be oil-cooled.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] In marine applications water-cooling is also used.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Expensive automobiles may use water-cooled alternators to meet high electrical system demands.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Most power generation stations use synchronous machines as their generators.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The connection of these generators to the utility grid requires synchronization conditions to be met.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Synchronous generators provide several important system services.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Their inherent rotational inertia slows the initial frequency decline after a sudden loss of generation, allowing turbine governors and other frequency-control reserves time to respond and restore balance.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] This role is increasingly significant as the share of non-synchronous generation, such as solar photovoltaics and many modern wind plants, grows in many power systems.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Alternators are used in modern internal combustion engine automobiles to charge the battery and to power the electrical system when its engine is running.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Until the 1960s, automobiles used DC dynamo generators with commutators.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] With the availability of affordable silicon-diode rectifiers, alternators were used instead.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] In later diesel–electric locomotives and diesel–electric multiple units, the prime mover turns an alternator which provides electricity for the traction motors (AC or DC).
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The traction alternator usually incorporates integral silicon diode rectifiers to provide the traction motors with up to 1,200 volts DC.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The first diesel electric locomotives, and many of those still in service, use DC generators as, before silicon power electronics, it was easier to control the speed of DC traction motors.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Most of these had two generators: one to generate the excitation current for a larger main generator.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Optionally, the generator also supplies head-end power (HEP) or power for electric train heating.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] The HEP option requires a constant engine speed, typically 900 r/min for a 480 V 60 Hz HEP application, even when the locomotive is not moving.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Marine alternators used in yachts are similar to automotive alternators, with appropriate adaptations to the salt-water environment.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Marine alternators are designed to be explosion proof (ignition protected) so that brush sparking will not ignite explosive gas mixtures in an engine room environment.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Depending on the type of system installed, they may be 12 or 24 volts.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Larger marine diesels may have two or more alternators to cope with the heavy electrical demand of a modern yacht.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] On single alternator circuits, the power may be split between the engine starting battery and the domestic or house battery (or batteries) by use of a split-charge diode (battery isolator) or a voltage-sensitive relay.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Due to the high cost of large house battery banks, Marine alternators generally use external regulators.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Multistep regulators control the field current to maximize the charging effectiveness (time to charge) and battery life.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Multistep regulators can be programmed for different battery types.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Two temperature sensors can be added: one for the battery to adjust the charging voltage and an over-temperature sensor on the actual alternator to protect it from overheating.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] High-frequency alternators of the variable-reluctance type were applied commercially to radio transmission in low-frequency radio bands.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] These were used for transmitting Morse code and, experimentally, for transmitting voice and music.
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] In the Alexanderson alternator, both the field winding and armature winding are stationary, and current is induced in the armature by the changing magnetic reluctance of the rotor (which has no windings or current-carrying parts).
[src:chrysler-valiant/alternator] Such machines were made to produce radio frequency current for radio transmissions, although the efficiency was low.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-design-rules] The **Australian Design Rules** (**ADRs**) are the national technical regulations for vehicle safety, theft resistance, and emissions requirements in Australia.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-design-rules] All new road vehicles manufactured in Australia and imported new or second-hand vehicles, must comply with the relevant ADRs when they are first supplied to the Australian market.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-design-rules] The relevant State or Territory government legislation generally requires that it complies with the relevant ADRs as at the time of manufacture.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-design-rules] The ADRs are largely based on and actively harmonised with the UN vehicle and equipment regulations.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-design-rules] An ADR may directly specify technical and performance requirements, as well as allow alternative standards to be met instead.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-design-rules] The alternative standards are typically the same UNECE regulations as those directly specified.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-design-rules] Most ADRs have been fully harmonised with UNECE regulations, meaning that a manufacturer only needs to provide evidence of a UNECE approval, or a valid test to the requirements of a regulation, in order to demonstrate compliance with an ADR.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-design-rules] Those ADRs that are only partially harmonised with UNECE Regulations require additional Australian requirements that must also be met.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-design-rules] Where an ADR is harmonised, the base text of the UNECE regulation forms the main text of the ADR.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-design-rules] The ADRs use only the technical requirements of the ECE Regulations; the ECE system of type approval is not used.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-design-rules] Vehicles configured in accordance with the regulations of countries other than Australia are generally barred from import to Australia unless they are brought into compliance with applicable ADRs and the conversion work is inspected and certified by an authorised compliance engineer.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-design-rules] As of 2024, the standards are the Third Edition ADRs, introduced in July 1989.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-design-rules] Since 1 July 2021, they have been administered by The Department of Infrastructure, Transport, Regional Development, Communications and the Arts under the Road Vehicle Standards Act 2018 (RVSA).
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-design-rules] From July 1989 until 1 July 2021, they were administered by the department under the Motor Vehicle Standards Act 1989 (MVSA).
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-design-rules] According to *Business Spectator* climate reporter Tristan Edis, as of early 2014 Australia's emissions standards as specified in the ADRs lagged behind those of most developed countries, and Australia was one of only a few major economies without fuel economy standards applying to cars.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-design-rules] The First Edition ADRs were only distributed for discussion and were not adopted as a legally binding set of Standards under either National or State/Territory law.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-design-rules] The Second Edition ADRs came into effect on 1 January 1969 and were selectively applied under State/Territory law.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-design-rules] They only applied to vehicles manufactured from 1 January 1969 onwards.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-design-rules] The Third Edition ADRs became effective from 1 July 1988.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-design-rules] In a transition period between 1 July 1988 and July 1989, the Second Edition ADRs were increasingly superseded by the Third Edition ADRs.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-design-rules] They were made National Standards by 1 September 1989.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-design-rules] The Third Edition ADRs were initially a combination of active Second Edition ADRs and amendments made in the interim after they were first published.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-design-rules] Amendments were made to ensure relevance, and new ADRs were added to cover new developments in road vehicle manufacturing and technology.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-design-rules] The application of ADRs for vehicles manufactured up until July 1989 is the responsibility of the State and Territory governments.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] The **pound** (sign: **£**, **£A** for distinction) was the currency of Australia from 1910 until 14 February 1966, when it was replaced by the Australian dollar.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] Like other £sd currencies, it was subdivided into 20 shillings (denoted by *s*), each of which was subdivided into 12 pence (denoted by *d*).
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] The establishment of a separate Australian currency was contemplated by section 51(xii) of the Constitution of Australia, which gave the Federal Parliament power to legislate with respect to "currency, coinage, and legal tender".
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] The Deakin government's *Coinage Act 1909* distinguished between "British coin" and "Australian coin", giving both status as legal tender of equal value.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] The Act gave the Treasurer the power to issue silver, bronze and nickel coins, with the dimensions, size, denominations, weight and fineness to be determined by proclamation of the Governor-General.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] The first coins were issued in 1910, produced by the Royal Mint in London.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] The Fisher Government's *Australian Notes Act 1910* gave the Governor-General the power to authorise the Treasurer to issue "Australian notes" as legal tender, "payable in gold coin on demand at the Commonwealth Treasury".
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] It also prohibited the circulation of state notes and withdrew their status as legal tender.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] In the same year the *Bank Notes Tax Act 1910* was passed imposing a prohibitive tax of 10% per annum on "all bank notes issued or re-issued by any bank in the Commonwealth after the commencement of this Act, and not redeemed", which effectively ended the use of private currency in Australia.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] As a transitional measure lasting three years, blank note forms of 16 banks were supplied to the government in 1911 to be overprinted as redeemable in gold and issued as the first Commonwealth notes.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] Some of these banknotes were overprinted by the treasury, and circulated as Australian banknotes until new designs were ready for Australia's first federal government-issued banknotes, which commenced in 1913.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] In May 2015, the National Library of Australia announced that it had discovered the first £A 1 banknote printed by the Commonwealth of Australia, among a collection of specimen banknotes.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] This uncirculated Australian pound note, with the serial number P000001 printed with red ink, was the first piece of currency to carry the coat of arms of Australia.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] The Australian currency was fixed in value to sterling.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] As such Australia was on the gold standard so long as Britain was.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] In 1914, the British government removed sterling from the gold standard.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] When it was returned to the gold standard in 1925, the sudden increase in its value (imposed by the nominal gold price) unleashed crushing deflationary pressures.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] Both the initial 1914 inflation and the subsequent 1926 deflation had far-reaching economic effects throughout the British Empire, Australia and the world.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] In 1929, as an emergency measure during the Great Depression, Australia left the gold standard, resulting in a devaluation relative to sterling.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] A variety of pegs to sterling applied until December 1931, when the government devalued the local unit by 20%, making one Australian pound equal to 16 shillings sterling (conversely, one pound sterling became equal to 25 Australian shillings).
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] Coins of the Australian pound also circulated freely in New Zealand, although they were never legal tender.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] By 1931, Australian coins made up approximately 30% of the total circulation in New Zealand.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] The devaluation of Australian and New Zealand exchange rates relative to the pound sterling led to New Zealand's *Coinage Act 1933* and the issuing of the first coinage of the New Zealand pound.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] During World War II, the Empire of Japan produced currency notes denominated in the Australian pound for use in Pacific island countries intended for occupation.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] Since mainland Australia was never occupied, the occupation currency was not used there, but it was used in the captured parts of the then-Australian territories of Papua and New Guinea.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] In 1949, when the United Kingdom devalued sterling against the US dollar, Australian Prime Minister and Treasurer Ben Chifley followed suit so the Australian pound would not become over-valued in sterling zone countries with which Australia did most of its external trade at the time.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] As one pound sterling went from US$4.03 to US$2.80, the Australian pound went from US$3.224 to US$2.24.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] Decimalisation had been proposed for Australian currency since 1902, when a select committee of the House of Representatives, chaired by George Edwards, had recommended that Australia adopt a decimal currency with the florin (two shillings) as its base.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] The committee presented its report in August 1960.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] It recommended the introduction of the new system on the second Monday in February 1963.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] In July 1961 the Commonwealth Government confirmed its support of a decimal currency system, but considered it undesirable to make final decisions on the detailed arrangement that would be necessary to effect the change.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] On 7 April 1963 the Commonwealth Government announced that a system of decimal currency was to be introduced into Australia at the earliest practicable date, and gave February 1966, as the tentative change-over date.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] On 14 February 1966, a decimal currency, the dollar of one hundred cents, was introduced.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] Under the implementation conversion rate, one pound was set as the equivalent of two dollars.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] Thus, ten shillings became one dollar, and one shilling became ten cents.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] As a shilling was equal to twelve pence, a cent was worth slightly more than a penny.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] In 1855, gold full and half sovereigns (worth, respectively, £1 and 10/– sterling) were first minted by the Sydney Mint.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] These coins were the only non-Imperial denominations issued by any of the Australian mints until after Federation (the Sydney Mint struck Imperial gold sovereigns and half sovereigns starting in 1871, and the Melbourne Mint starting in 1872).
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] In 1910, .925 fineness sterling silver coins were minted in denominations of 3d, 6d, 1/– and 2/– (known as a *Trey*, *Zac*, *Deena*, and *Florin* respectively).
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] Unusually no half crown (worth 2/6) was ever issued.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] Bronze 1⁄2d and 1d coins followed in 1911.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] Production of half sovereigns ceased in 1916, followed by that of sovereigns in 1931.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] In 1937 a crown (5/– piece, known as a *Dollar*) was issued to commemorate the coronation of King George VI.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] This coin proved unpopular in circulation and was discontinued shortly after being reissued in 1938.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] In 1946, the fineness of Australian silver sixpences, shillings, and florins was reduced to .500, a quarter of a century after the same change had been made in Britain.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] In New Zealand and the United Kingdom, silver was soon abandoned completely in everyday coinage, but Australian .500 silver coins continued to be minted until after decimalisation.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] Examples of private issue paper currency in New South Wales, denominated in sterling, exist from 1814 (and may date back to the 1790s).
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] Denominated in sterling (and in some cases Spanish dollars), these private banker and merchant scrip notes were used in Sydney and Hobart through 1829.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] Private issue banknotes were issued between 1817 and 1910 in denominations ranging from £1 to £100.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] In 1910, superscribed banknotes were used as the Commonwealth's first national paper currency until the Treasury began issuing Commonwealth banknotes in 1913.
[src:chrysler-valiant/australian-pound] The Commonwealth Bank Act of 1920 gave note-issuing authority to the Commonwealth Bank.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The **Chrysler Valiant** is a full-size car which was sold by Chrysler Australia between 1962 and 1981.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Initially a rebadged locally assembled Plymouth Valiant from the United States, from the second generation launched in 1963, the Valiant was fully manufactured in Australia.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] It was sold locally but also in New Zealand and South Africa, with smaller numbers also exported to South-East Asia and the United Kingdom.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Parent company Chrysler made a substantial investment in Australian manufacturing facilities by establishing operations in South Australia with an assembly plant at Tonsley Park in 1964 and an engine foundry at Lonsdale in 1968.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The Valiant thus established its position as the third of the "Big 3" Australian-made vehicles behind the Holden Kingswood and Ford Falcon.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The Australian Valiant was built on the North American A-body platform but with many parts and components from Australian suppliers.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Apart from a sedan and wagon body style, 1965 saw the introduction of a commercial utility that was badged the **Wayfarer** and later exported to South Africa as the **Rustler**.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Greater differentiation from the donor car crept in over time, particularly since the VE series, which was embraced by the Australian motoring press and won the 1967 *Wheels* magazine Car of the Year award.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The VF series of 1969 and the VG of 1970 departed even further from its North American donor both in terms of styling and performance—with the latter series introducing the *Hemi-6* engine that replaced the *Slant-6*.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Moreover, Australia continued to produce a station wagon model, called the **Safari**, even after this body style was discontinued for North America.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Beginning in 1971, the VH series saw Chrysler Australia develop the entire lineup locally including the Charger.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Local design and production continued until the CM series of 1979, which marked the end of local production in 1981, after the takeover of operations by Mitsubishi Motors Australia.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] After the Plymouth Valiant turned out to be a success in the United States (starting with its 1959 introduction), Chrysler released Australia's first locally assembled Valiant, the RV1 (R-series).
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] It was officially unveiled by South Australia's Premier, Sir Thomas Playford, in January 1962 and was assembled at Chrysler's Mile End facility.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The RV1 (or R Series) Valiant was an instant success.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Not everyone was taken instantly by the car's styling, but the general consensus was that the car had a modern, almost space age quality about it.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Also notable was the Valiant's performance with 145 brake horsepower (108 kW) from the 225 *Slant-6* engine.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] This was a lot of power compared to the competing Holdens and Fords, which offered only 75 bhp (56 kW) and 90 bhp (67 kW) SAE respectively.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Standard transmission in the RV1 was a floor-shifted three-speed manual with a non-synchro first gear.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] A button-operated three-speed TorqueFlite automatic was optional.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Other options included a heater-demister unit, as well as a "Moparmatic" deluxe pushbutton transistor radio.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The RV1 Valiant was the first Australian car to come with an alternator instead of a generator, and instead of coil springs, the Valiant came with torsion bar suspension.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Brakes were hydraulic 9" drums front and rear.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The RV1 had a simulated spare wheel outline on the bootlid, but the spare wheel was actually under the floor of the boot.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] In March 1962, Chrysler replaced the American 1961-model R Valiant with the American 1962 SV1 (S Series) Valiant.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The SV1 used the same body shell as the RV1, with cosmetic changes including the deletion of the simulated spare wheel on the bootlid, and round tail lamps replacing the R-model's cat-eye shaped ones.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] There was a revised radiator grille and new exterior trim.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Mechanical changes included relocation of the manual transmission shifter to the steering column, new ball joints, and a new gear-reduction starter motor.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] 10,009 SV1 Valiants were sold, of which 5,496 were automatics and 4,513 were manuals.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] On 30 May 1963, Chrysler Australia produced the first fully Australian manufactured Valiant, the **AP5**.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] In February of that year, Chrysler Australia had begun work on its new $36 million Tonsley Park facility in South Australia, where it could boost annual production to 50 thousand cars.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The new plant produced its first Valiants on 31 March 1964.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The AP5 ("AP" for *Australian Production*) was an entirely new design with only the four doors, windscreen, and front guards shared with its North American counterpart.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Initial cars retained the left-hand-drive wiper pattern but this was soon changed to a RHD layout.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The *Slant-6* driveline was retained, but the AP5 was considerably more straightforward in styling than its R- and S-model antecedents.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] With high local content and specifications optimised for local conditions, this new Valiant strengthened the brand's position in the marketplace.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] A new upmarket **Regal** version was included in the range.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] In November 1963 an AP5 **Safari** station wagon was released.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Total production of the AP5 range amounted to 49,440 vehicles.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] In March 1965, the AP5 was supplanted by the **AP6**.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The body shell was the same, but there was a new grille on the theme of the 1964 North American Plymouth Barracuda, and there was new trim inside and out.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The automatic transmission was no longer controlled by pushbuttons, but instead by a conventional shift lever.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The AP6 also included other new features such as self-adjusting brakes and acrylic enamel paint, at the time the most advanced auto finish available.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The AP6 model range included the **Valiant Wayfarer**, the first Valiant-based coupe utility to be built by Chrysler Australia.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The AP6 was the first Australian-built Valiant to be offered with a V8 engine – the 273 cu in (4.47 L) LA V8, introduced in American Valiants in 1964, and released in Australia in August 1965.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The engine developed 180 brake horsepower (130 kW) and pushed the Valiant to a top speed of 109 mph (175 km/h).
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The V8 was only available as a model in its own right, the V8 Valiant, which had a vinyl-covered roof, individual bucket seats, floor console mounted automatic shift lever and two-tone steering wheel.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The *Slant-6'*s camshaft was also slightly upgraded for improved torque by dint of increased duration and lift.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Chrysler Australia had difficulty meeting demand, with the Valiant being built at Tonsley Park at a maximum rate of 200 cars per eight-hour shift.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Customers had to wait up to four months for delivery of a new AP6.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The VC Valiant was introduced in March 1966 and, although underneath it was basically the same car as the preceding AP6 Series, the body was extensively restyled giving the illusion of being longer and lower.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The modern new design was highlighted by sharp, squared-off edges and corners clearly influenced by Chrysler in the United States.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The front now had a full-width horizontal grille while the rear was also much squarer with vertical taillights.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The range of models again consisted of the Valiant standard or Regal sedan, standard or Safari Regal wagon and Wayfarer utility.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] They featured higher standard equipment levels as well as new safety features, such as optional disc brakes on V8 models, which were named 'Valiant V8/Safari V8' and were essentially Regal models.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] In total, Chrysler Australia built 65,634 VC Series models.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] This Valiant was an all-new design introduced in October 1967, based on the North American platform, which had a 108 in (2,700 mm) wheelbase.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The bonnet and guards were shared with the also-new 1967 North American Dodge Dart, with other styling cues otherwise inherited from the North American Valiant.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The car featured slightly larger body dimensions and greater interior space than the preceding VC Series.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The roofline was also flattened out and the rear window was given a concave profile.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Higher levels of standard equipment were featured and two engine options became available.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The basic *Slant-6* was retained with its 145 bhp (108 kW) rating, but a new 2-barrel carbureted version was released with output of 160 bhp (120 kW).
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The 273 V8 was also improved and made available across the entire Valiant range.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] All models benefited from additional safety features (some compulsory under new Australian Design Rules, or ADRs) such as dual circuit brakes with a tandem master cylinder, double sided safety rims, front seat belts and front power disc brakes on V8 models.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The VE range consisted of Valiant & Valiant Regal sedans, Valiant Safari & Valiant Regal Safari station wagons and Valiant, Valiant Wayfarer & Dodge utilities, the latter being a lower-priced version of the Valiant utility.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The flagship model followed on from the AP6 and VC V8 theme, being similarly equipped with bucket seats, floor shift automatic, and vinyl roof all standard, but was given the new name "VIP" to distinguish it from other models, since the V8 engine option was made available across the range.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] It also shared the 3 'sergeant stripes' of the VC V8 on the rear quarter panel.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The biggest accolade for the VE Valiant was *Wheels* "Car of the Year" in 1967 – the first for Chrysler Australia.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] In March 1969, the VE was replaced by the **VF** model.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The new car shared its middle section with the previous VE Valiant, but there was new front and rear styling.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The new front end featured a horizontally convex grille, replacing the VE's concave design.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The front indicators were placed at the top leading edge of the front guards rather than in a more conventional location in the grille or front bumper.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] This allowed the VF's front bumper to be thinner and less prominent, which made the single round headlights look larger, and the front end appeared more aggressive as a result.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Valiant and Valiant Regal models were once again available, and the VF range also saw the introduction of the **Valiant Regal 770** and an upgraded VIP model.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The VF VIP was introduced two months after the Valiant range and was no longer a Valiant V.I.P. but was now marketed as a **Chrysler VIP**, in sedan form only.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] It offered a stretched (112 inches or 2,800 millimetres) wheelbase, with longer rear doors than the Valiant.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] As with previous model changes, the VF boasted even more safety features including a padded instrument panel and energy absorbing steering column.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] A larger 5.2 L (318 cu in) version of the LA V8 replaced the 273, taking the V8's top speed to 109 mph (175 km/h).
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Transmission options remained the same: three-speed manual or three-speed TorqueFlite automatic.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The most significant introduction to the VF range was the all new two-door Valiant Hardtop – essentially, a North American Dodge Dart coupé with the Australian Valiant front sheetmetal and interior trim.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] At over 5,000 mm (200 in), it is the longest coupe ever built in Australia.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Released six months after the other VF Valiants in September 1969, it was available in Valiant, Valiant Regal and Valiant Regal 770 models.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] In mid 1969, Chrysler released a fast four-door named **Valiant Pacer**.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] A low-cost, high-power version of the bread-and-butter Valiant sedan, the Pacer featured a high-performance six-cylinder engine and three-speed manual gearbox with floor shifter.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Despite a lack of exterior chrome, the VF Pacer stood out with its red and black grille, simulated-mag wheel hub caps, special body striping, 'Pacer 225' decals, and choice of "Wild Blue", "Wild Red", or "Wild Yellow" exterior colours.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The sparsely trimmed interior featured high back bucket seats, and distinctive black on white instrument dials with a dash-top-mounted tachometer.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Although lacking the V8 of its rivals, the Pacer could reach almost 180 km/h (112 mph) and, at $2798, was $400 cheaper than the base GTS Monaro.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The Pacer was powered by a special version of the trusty 225 *Slant-6*.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] With two-barrel carburettor, high-flow exhaust system, and 9.3:1 compression ratio, it produced 175 bhp (130 kW).
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Standard brakes were finned, servo-assisted drum brakes all round, although most buyers opted for the optional front discs.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Underneath was Valiant's basic torsion bar suspension, lowered by 125 mm (5 in) to improve handling and with a front anti-sway bar fitted.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] A 'Sure-Grip' limited-slip differential with either 3.23:1 or 2.92:1 ratios was optional.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Contemporary road testers were mostly full of praise for the Pacer, noting there were few cars that could match it on a performance for price basis.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] *Modern Motor* (May, 1969) took a VF Pacer sedan to 60 mph (97 km/h) in a respectable 10.5 seconds, the 1⁄4 mile (400 m) in 17.5 seconds and topped out at 111 mph (179 km/h).
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] In 1969, Chrysler's market share reached 13.7%.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] In total, 52,944 VF Valiants were built.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] August 1970 saw the introduction of another facelifted version of the VE/VF bodystyle in the **VG** Valiant.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The VG's most noticeable difference was the use of rectangular headlamps instead of the traditional round ones (except on VIP models, which used quad round headlamps).
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The guard-top indicator location was carried over from the VF.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The grille was a horizontal, single-plane item, and the taillamps were revised and wrapped around to the body side.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Sedan, Wagon, Ute and Hardtop body styles were offered once again as well as the same luxury levels as before.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The biggest announcement to come with the VG Valiant was of the all new *Hemi-6 engine*, replacing the *Slant-6*.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The new engine was introduced as a 245 cu in (4.0 L) unit with quasi-hemispherical combustion chambers.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The "*Hemi*" name was already legendary in America with Chrysler's use of the *Hemi V8*, hence Chrysler Australia's marketing leverage for its 6-cylinder offering.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The sporty Pacer sedan was available again, but whereas the VF Pacer was only offered with the one power output, the new VG Pacer offered 3 different versions of the new 245 *Hemi-6* engine, though Chrysler Australia didn't publish any power output figures for the Pacers.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The standard Pacer had a 2-barrel carburettor and produced 185 bhp (138 kW).
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] **Option E31** produced 195 bhp (145 kW) and included a two-barrel carburettor, higher-performance camshaft, smaller fan, and windage tray.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] **Option E35** included a 4-barrel carburettor, high-performance camshaft, heavy-duty engine bearings, a dual-plate clutch, torque-limiting engine mount strut, and the ordinary Pacer-spec transmission.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The VG series Pacers were also the first and last to be offered in the Hardtop body style, of which three were optioned with the E31 package and three were optioned with E35 package.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] No VG Pacer Hardtops were available with the E34 option.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Due to Chrysler Australia's policy (local content law/government law) of using only locally produced components, and the unavailability of a local four-speed gearbox, the Pacer was offered with only a three-speed floor shift manual transmission.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] A total of 46,374 VG Valiants were built.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Chrysler released the VH Valiant range in June 1971.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The VH was designed by Chrysler in the United States with input from Australian engineers to be an Australia-only model range.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] It was a major change from the preceding VG range – these were larger cars, styled to look even larger than they were.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The grille treatment on the new VH range was a direct design descendant from the US Mopars with the central recessed area for grille and headlamps, surrounded by uninterrupted trim on the outer leading edge of the whole assembly.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The rectangular headlamps were carried over from the VG model.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The model range of the VH Valiant was quite extensive, starting with the new entry-level Valiant Ranger, and progressing to Valiant Ranger XL, Valiant Pacer, Valiant Regal, and Valiant Regal 770.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Carried over from the VG range, the basic *Hemi-6* 245ci engine was standard equipment for Ranger XL and Regal, but a new 265 cu in (4.3 L) version offered 203 bhp (151 kW) and was standard equipment for the Regal 770.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The *Fireball* 318 V8 engine was still an option, but only available on the Regal 770 sedan.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The basic Ranger sedan featured a new low compression *Hemi-6* 215ci engine that operated on Standard grade petrol.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] This engine was not available on the other sedan cars in the VH range.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Unlike the VG range, Valiant Pacer was now only available in 4-door sedan form.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Apart from vivid paint colours, optional bonnet blackouts and striping, the new Pacer featured a higher performance version of the 265ci engine, with 218 bhp (163 kW) at 4,800 rpm and 273 lbf⋅ft (370 N⋅m) at 3,000 rpm.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The Pacer could run the quarter-mile in 15.9 seconds, get to 100 km/h in 7.6 seconds and reach a top speed of 185 km/h.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] In fact, at its release, the VH Valiant Pacer set the record for being the fastest mass-produced four-door sedan with a six-cylinder engine manufactured in Australia, a record which stood for 17 years.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The Pacer's days as the VH performance model were numbered, because that same year saw the announcement and introduction of what was to become Chrysler Australia's most recognised new car – the Valiant Charger.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] In total, only 1,647 VH Valiant Pacer sedans were produced.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The new Valiant Charger was unlike anything that had come before and it had the Australian motoring press calling it, "...the most handsome car Chrysler has ever produced, and probably the best looking car ever produced by an Australian manufacturer".
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] A short-wheelbase, fastback coupe with an aggressive wedge-like stance, the Charger's design gave the effect of speed, even when it was standing still.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Chrysler's TV campaign for the Charger featured the young adults at whom it was targeted, waving at one as it swept by them and shouting "Hey, Charger!" One of the more memorable TV ads of the time, it created a cliché that haunts today's owners.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Charger won *Wheels* magazine's Car of the Year award for 1971 and was widely acclaimed by others in the motoring press, as well as the public.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The Valiant Charger came in four model guises, closely mirroring the existing sedan range – Charger, Charger XL, Charger 770, and Charger R/T.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The first of the serious "track pack" R/T Chargers had option E38.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Despite being hampered by a three-speed gearbox, it still drew favourable comments from *Wheels*: "We achieved a time of 14.8 seconds for the quarter-mile – on smoother surfaces the Charger galloped away so easily that a best of 14.5 seconds is within reach".
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Being a three-speed gearbox, these quarter-mile runs took only one gear change.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The most recognised performance Chargers were the **Six Pack** cars.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The term *six pack* denoted the triple side-draught Weber 2BBL carburettors with which the 265 *Hemi-6* engine – in option E37, option E38, and later option E49 – produced levels of power unheard of on a naturally aspirated six-cylinder at the time.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The triple carburettors also made for a distinctive throaty note when under acceleration.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] E38 versions of the Charger R/T featured a 265 *Hemi-6* which produced 280 bhp (209 kW) while the E37 was the street tune option made available on Charger 770 and Charger R/T.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] E38 was a race-ready Charger R/T with the additional A84 Track Pack option, which included a 35-imperial-gallon (160 L) fuel tank.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] There was also an A87 Track Pack option that included all the race track goodies, but for the larger fuel tank.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] In mid-1972, the E38 option was superseded by the more powerful and greatly refined four-speed transmission E49 option.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] This drew comments from *Wheels* such as, "The raw quivering power is instantaneously on tap and with a ratio for every conceivable situation the Charger just storms through.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] It would take a Ferrari Daytona with racing driver Jackie Ickx at the wheel to stay with one".
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] All E49s came with a Track Pack, 21 of which featured the huge fuel tank with dual fillers.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The E49 six pack engine came with a baffled sump, tuned length headers, special shot-peened crankshaft, connecting rods, pistons, rings, cam, valve springs, a twin plate clutch and of course the triple 45 mm dual throat Weber carburetors.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Chrysler quoted this engine as producing 302 bhp (225 kW), with the car weighing 1,372 kg (3,025 lb).
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The R/T E49 was the ultimate Valiant Charger, and with only 149 built the E49s are still widely considered today as one of the greatest Australian "muscle" cars ever produced.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Road tests of the era recorded quarter-mile times of between 14.1 and 14.5 seconds.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] This compares to times of 14.6 for the next quickest accelerating Australian muscle car, the Ford XY Falcon GT-HO (Phase III).
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Although the Six Pack Chargers were the dominant performance players in the VH range, there was another Charger, the 275 bhp (205 kW), 340 cu in (5.6 L) V8 powered E55, that came close.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Option E55 was applied to the new Charger 770 SE in August 1972, and this car could reach 60 mph (97 km/h) in 7.2 seconds and complete the quarter-mile in 15.5 seconds – all topped off by a top speed of 122 mph (196 km/h).
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] A batch of several hundred VH Charger 770 318 V8s were exported to Japan along with CH sedans.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The Chargers had a CH-like nose with VH sheet metal surrounding the CH four headlights and grille, a combination that NZ assembler Todd Motors would later use to create its unique VJ Valiant Regal 770 sedan.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The Japanese cars also had air conditioning, side marker lights and separate white reversing lights as well as mirrors conforming to Japanese market regulations.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Overall, Chrysler Australia manufactured 67,800 VH Valiant cars.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] New Zealand distributor Todd Motors had assembled the Valiant sedan from CKD kits since the AP5, mostly following the Australian range though with fewer variants and engine choices plus local upholstery.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The Regal 770 had the 265ci *Hemi-6*, floor-console automatic shifter, round dials with wood trim in place of the strip speedo and its own unique front bucket seats and trim.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The 318ci V8 was optional and a vinyl roof was standard but could be deleted to order.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Todd's sole locally built Charger model was also to '770' trim with the 265ci *Hemi-6* six and three-speed floor shift auto and did not have the bumper overriders standard in Australia.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Early runs had one-piece front door glass and hinged opening rear side windows but, due to problems with water leaks and excessive wind noise, this was soon changed to opening front quarterlights and fixed rear side glass.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Wagons were imported from Australia, to Australian specification.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] VH Valiants were assembled at Silverton, near Pretoria in South Africa using Australian bodies, electrics and trim and locally sourced mechanical components including a 225 cid engine.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Prior to 1971 South African Valiants had been sourced from Canada.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The VH model range also saw the introduction of the new luxury class vehicles, the **CH** range.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The CH was a further 4 inches (100 mm) longer in the wheelbase than the VH Valiant – 115 in (2,900 mm) – with a total length of 197 in (5,000 mm).
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] It featured quad round headlamps and a different rear end treatment, and had quieter suspension and higher equipment levels.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The CH (or "Chrysler by Chrysler", as it is commonly referred to) was a four-door luxury model intended to compete with the Ford Fairlane and Holden's Statesman models in the luxury car market in Australia.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Also released in October 1971 was a two-door version of the CH which was called the Chrysler Hardtop, and shared the same wheelbase as the four-door Chrysler, along with the front and rear end treatment.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] May 1973 saw the introduction of the next model in the new All-Australian designed Valiant – The **VJ**.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Although essentially a facelifted version of the VH Valiant before it, the VJ's subtle changes made enough of an impact on the buying public to make it the biggest selling Chrysler Valiant model of all, with 90,865 units being sold.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Externally the VJ Valiant continued on with the VH series body styles, though the VJ reverted to single 7" round headlamps and a new 8-segment grille.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] VJ sedans also received new horizontal taillights.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Although the physical changes were few, many other new features were introduced in the VJ Valiant range, such as electronic ignition, rustproofing and floor-mounted shifters as standard features.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Chrysler upgraded equipment levels in July 1974 with front disc brakes, door reflectors, lockable glovebox and retractable seatbelts all as standard features.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] While the VJ range still offered sedan, wagon, ute, hardtop and coupe variants, the performance-oriented Pacer sedans and Charger R/T coupes were deleted from the new range.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] However, a variation of the E37 Six Pack engine (now with four-speed manual transmission) was made available, in the form of option E48, with most of the cars bearing this option ending up being base model VJ Charger coupes.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Four VJ Charger coupes were built by special order featuring the VH series option E49 engine.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The other carry-over performance variant was option E55, with the 340ci V8 engine option officially remaining as restricted to Charger 770 coupe application only.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] In August 1974, a special run of 500 Sportsman coupes were released, based upon the Charger XL model.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] They were only available in Vintage Red with white body accents.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] These cars also had a unique white interior with plaid cloth seats and featured a standard 265 engine with a choice of either manual or automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] In New Zealand, Todd Motors was even more adventurous with the VJ.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The base Ranger XL and Charger were updated, as in Australia, with similar NZ-only variations as the VH but the VJ Regal 770 was something of a 'parts bin special' and essentially a merger of a VJ Regal with a CH Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The nose – also used for several hundred VH Chargers built for the Japanese market – combined the CH's four headlamps and grille with VH Valiant sheetmetal (retaining the older, larger, clear park/indicator lamps) while the rest of the body was as per Australian VJ.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Inside, new front seats were CH style, with individual chairs forming a bench shape, and a column automatic shifter was now used.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Earlier cars had all-vinyl upholstery but cloth was fitted as standard later.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] New Zealand VJ Regals also had a vinyl roof in black or beige and the panel between the tail lights was also trimmed in vinyl to match – the vinyl trim could be deleted to order.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The Chrysler was given a facelift in May 1973 to become the CJ Series.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The two-door hardtop was dropped leaving only the four-door sedan to carry on the fight against its Ford and Statesman luxury competitors.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The related Valiant hardtop's production continued.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] In October 1975 the VK Valiant was released with few external changes from the previous VJ model.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The Ranger now had an argent version of the VJ Charger grille, the Charger XL had a white version and the Charger 770 also had the argent grille.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The VK Valiant Regal featured a "grille within a grille".
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The Ranger sedan, Regal sedan, and Charger all now shared the same tail-light treatment, using a horizontal layout with four chrome contours to keep air flow away and keep the lenses clean.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The Chargers were not called Chrysler Valiant Chargers any longer; with the 'Valiant' name being dropped.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The VK Regal also had blinker repeaters housed in small chrome boxes which sat on top of both front guards.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Another unusual option was the **Fuel Pacer** option from the Chrysler US parts bin which detected low engine vacuum – as under hard acceleration – and illuminated the driver side guardtop blinker repeater to indicate wasteful driving.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Inertia-reel seatbelts and slightly different heater controls were introduced on the VK, as well as a combination control stalk for the lights and wipers from the Mitsubishi Galant.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The Ranger also got full-length door trims, and carpet was now standard.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] VK six-cylinder series engines were the same as the VJ's, and the 245 *Hemi-6* now featured a two-barrel carburettor like the 265 variant.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The V8s were mainly 318 cu in (5.2 L) units, though the 360 cu in (5.9 L) remained an option across the entire range.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] It was not very popular as the mid-1970s saw the trend towards smaller cars with smaller motors.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] While the "three on the tree" column shift manual gearbox was still available, it was rarely specified (although still popular on Utes) and the three-speed floor change was now gone too.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Buyers seeking floor-shift manual could choose the four-speed, which was available on all models but could only be had with a *Hemi-6*, not with a V8.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Late in the VK model run a limited edition Charger called the White Knight Special (option A50) was offered with a factory-fitted front air dam.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The changes were mainly cosmetic with running gear being largely stock.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] There were 200 White Knight Specials made – 100 Arctic White and 100 Amarante Red.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] 120 were automatics and 80 were four-speeds.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] 20,555 VK Valiants were produced and production ceased in June 1976.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] This was because ADR 27A for exhaust emission control became effective on 1 July 1976, and all the car manufacturers used that date as the introduction of a new model to comply with the new standard.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] VK assembly did not begin in New Zealand until nearly a year after Australian launch because a 60% sales tax levied on large engine cars, introduced during the 1973-4 oil crisis, drastically slowed VJ sales.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The model range in New Zealand was pared down to Regal and Regal 770 editions.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] A version of the Regal was manufactured for the South African Police as the SPP package in the late 1970s which featured triple carburetors, an uprated gearbox, uprated differential, and larger disc brakes.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The Chrysler was given a slight a facelift in October 1975 to become the **CK** series.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Production ceased just one year later in October 1976 when the Chrysler was replaced by the Chrysler Regal SE, a prestige version of the CL Series Valiant.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The CL Series Valiant was introduced in November 1976.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Although it used the same bodyshell as the previous VK range, the front and rear ends were restyled.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The front end used horizontally arrayed quad round headlamps flanking a central grille.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The front guards and bonnet were also reworked accordingly.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The new bootlid's curved leading edge flowed down to new taillights that sandwiched a simple centre garnish panel.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The bumpers, however, were the same units as had been used on the 1969 VF series Valiants.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The Ranger name was dropped; the base model CL was simply called *Valiant*, and the long-wheelbase "Chrysler by Chrysler" was replaced by the *Regal SE*.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The CL series Regal was marketed as the **Chrysler Regal**, in contrast to the Valiant Regal name used from the AP5 series through to the recently superseded VK Series.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The CL series was the last to include a Charger model, which – like the previous VK model – was badged and sold as a *Chrysler*, not as a *Valiant* submodel.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The CL Charger was generally available in only one trim level, the **Charger 770**, though a **Charger XL** was made available to police departments.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The CL series also saw the arrival of the panel van variant to compete with similar offerings from rival makers.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Interiors carried over largely unchanged from the VK range, though the Regal SE offered luxurious buttoned-leather seating as an option.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Base Valiants continued with the previous Ranger style strip speedometer, while the Regal dash featured recessed circular gauges and clock with a woodgrain finish.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The Charger 770 dash was similar to that of the Regal, except it was finished in black and had a tachometer instead of a clock.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The 3.5 L (215 cu in) *Hemi-6* and 5.9 L (360 cu in) V8 were dropped, and the only engine options were low- and high-compression versions of the 4.0 L (245 cu in) *Hemi-6* and the 5.2 L (318 cu in) V8.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The CL's introduction had closely coincided with that of the strict exhaust emission regulations contained in ADR 27A.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] With the 318 engine, a new emissions control system was introduced: **Electronic Lean Burn**.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Transmission options were 3-speed manual with floor or column shift, four-speed manual with floor shift, and three-speed Torqueflite automatic with floor or column shift.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The automatic was standard equipment with the 318 V8, and optional with a 6-cylinder.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The 4-speed was optional for six- and eight-cylinder models.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The floor-shift auto option was fitted to most Regals and all Regal SE's.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] In 1978 Chrysler released a limited edition run of 400 special **Regal Le Baron** models (option A17).
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The Le Baron was available only in Silver, with red or blue interiors.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The 265 *Hemi-6* was standard, and the 318 V8 was optional.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Valiant and Regal sedans also benefited from the 1978 introduction of *Radial Tuned Suspension* in response to Holden's having marketed their suspension as particularly suited to radial tyres.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] RTS improved the car's handling and roadholding significantly, and "Modern Motor" magazine proclaimed that the Valiant offered a better drive than the Holden.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The last special option in the CL range was the $816 **Drifter** package, available on the Charger.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The Drifter package included Impact Orange, Sundance Yellow, Spinnaker White or Harvest Gold body paint, and large side and rear stripes.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Drifters in white had additional "strobe stripes" on the bootlid.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Engine options were again the 265 six or 318 V8, but the 4-speed manual was the only transmission option.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] A Drifter Pack was also offered on the Valiant Panel Van and on the Utility.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] 36,672 CL Valiants – including the last-ever Chargers – were built.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The CL was the last Valiant series assembled in New Zealand – by now the Chargers and Ranger were gone and the Regal and the Regal SE, replacing the 770, were the only models.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The Regal SE was the first car to be assembled in the country with standard air conditioning.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The CM was released in November 1978, and was little changed bodywise from the CL model.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Only sedan and wagon models were produced.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] A sports sedan called the GLX (option A16) was released as a replacement for the discontinued Charger and earlier the Pacer.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Its features included a Charger grill and dashboard, special cloth trim, Cheviot Hotwire mag wheels and black door frames.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] It was advertised as the car "For People Who Like Their Cars Rare", as it was the last of the sports models and the jewel in the CM series.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The GLX could be optioned with a 4.3 L (265 cu in) *Hemi-6* or 5.2 L (318 cu in) V8.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The computer-controlled Electronic Lean Burn system continued giving favourable fuel economy; when *Wheels* performed an economy test in 1979, they found the ELB-equipped Valiant 4.0 L (245 cu in) used less fuel than a 2.0 L (120 cu in) Ford Cortina.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] A Valiant achieved better than 30 miles per imperial gallon (9.4 L/100 km) in the Total Oil Economy Run.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Production of this car continued after Mitsubishi's takeover of Chrysler's Australian operations.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Mitsubishi could build the car profitably even in small numbers due to its high 97% level of local Australian content and amortised tooling.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] However, the car was still badged as the *Chrysler* Valiant, not as a Mitsubishi.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The profit from the sale of one Valiant was equal to the profit from 3 Mitsubishi Sigmas- by this time the company's main seller.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Valiant production ended in August 1981 with production of the CM reaching 16,005 units out of 565,338 units of all models.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Eventually, the Mitsubishi Magna was developed to replace both the Sigma and Valiant.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Full-sized Chryslers were not marketed again in Australia until the 2005 release of the Chrysler 300C.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Although the Charger is arguably the best remembered Valiant in Australian motorsport, earlier models achieved class wins at the annual "Bathurst 500" production car race, something that the Charger never did.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] A Valiant AP5 won Class D at the 1963 Armstrong 500, a VC Valiant V8 won Class D at the 1966 Gallaher 500 and a VG Valiant Pacer won Class D at the 1970 Hardie-Ferodo 500.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Chargers were raced in the Hardie-Ferodo 500 at Bathurst in 1971 and 1972 with factory support.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] They gained a best placing of third outright and second in class in 1972.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Chrysler's policy was to race "Australian made" product, which meant the race cars ran 4.3 L (265 cu in) six-cylinder engines equipped with triple Weber carburettors and 3-speed gearboxes.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] Even skilled driving and good engineering could not defeat Ford's legendary Falcon GTHO Phase III with its 351 cu in (5.75 L) V8.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] In New Zealand, however, the Chryslers proved to be virtually unbeatable from 1971 to 1979 at the famous B&H 500-mile (later 1000 km) series at Pukekohe Park Raceway.
[src:chrysler-valiant/chrysler-valiant] The most successful drivers were Leo Leonard and Jim Little, who still races his Valiants (mostly pre-65 class).
